// A list literal bound to `any` is built as a list, then erased.
//
// The checker adopts an expected type wholesale for a list literal (unlike a record
// literal, whose type is nominal and independent of the expectation), so `let li: any =
// [1, 2, 3]` typed the literal itself as `any`. Lowering then emitted `MakeList` with a
// result repr of `Any`, and the backend had no element repr to size the slots or pick the
// value-witness with. It used to guess `List[any]`: 24-byte slots written with 8-byte
// `i64`s, and a witness that does not exist. Now the list is built at `List[i64]` and a
// separate `Cast` erases it -- the same build-then-erase shape a record literal has.
//
// The binding must be *used*. `MakeList` is pure, so an unused one is removed by DCE and
// the bug disappears with it.
//
// `is List[i64]` is true because the type argument is part of the answer: a box's tag
// spells the whole repr, not its head. `is List[str]` on this value is false, which is
// what erased_generic_is_checks_arguments.neon exists to pin down. The `is str` case here
// shows the answer distinguishes rather than being blanket-true.

use std::io;

fn is_list(a: any) -> bool { a is List[i64] }
fn is_str(a: any) -> bool { a is str }

fn main() {
    let li: any = [1, 2, 3];
    io::println("#{is_list(li)}");
    io::println("#{is_str(li)}");
}
